::: {.callout-note title="Question"}

Use `mosaicplot()` from base `R` to visualize the contingency table. 

:::

::::: {.content-visible when-profile="solution"}  

::: {.callout-tip}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mosaicplot(~ CATEGORIE + SEXE, 
           tb, 
           main="Données Recensement, ~ CATEGORIE + SEXE", 
           las=2)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](lab-bivariate_files/figure-html/mosaics-1-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mosaicplot(~ SEXE + CATEGORIE, 
           tb, 
           main="Données Recensement, ~ SEXE + CATEGORIE",
           las=2)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](lab-bivariate_files/figure-html/mosaics-2-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


Mosaic plots belong to the family of area plots. For each couple of levels, a rectangle is plotted with surface area proportional to the frequency of the couple of levels. 

In a 2-way mosaicplots, the width of the rectangles is proportional to the marginal count of the levels of the variable mapped to the `X` axis (first variable in the formula). For each level says `a` of the `X` variable, the height of the subrectangle corresponding to a level say `b` of the `Y` variable  is proportional to the ratio between the frequency if couple `(a,b)` and the marginal frequency of `a`.

The mosaicplot with formula `~ CATEGORIE + SEXE` allows us to visualize the frequencies of the different levels of `CATEGORIE`, and for each level of `CATEGORIE` the sex ratio of that level. 


:::

:::::

::: {.callout-note title="Question"}

Use `geom_mosaic` from `ggmosaic` to visualize the contingency table
while complying with the `ggplot2` look and feel.

- Make the plot as readable as possible
- Reorder `CATEGORIE` acccording to counts

:::

::::: {.content-visible when-profile="solution"}  

::: {.callout-tip}

The next layer will be used repeatedly. 


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
rot_x_text <- ggplot2::theme(
  axis.text.x = ggplot2::element_text(angle = 45)
)

old_theme <- ggplot2::theme_set(theme_minimal())

theme_update(
  axis.text.x = ggplot2::element_text(angle = 45),
  legend.position="None")
```
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
df |>
  ggplot2::ggplot() +
  ggmosaic::geom_mosaic(
    ggplot2::aes(
      x=ggmosaic::product(SEXE, CATEGORIE), 
     fill=SEXE)) +
  # ggplot2::scale_fill_brewer(
  #   palette ="Greys"
  # ) +
  ggtitle(label="")
```
:::

:::

:::::

::: {.callout-note title="Question"}

- Collapse rare levels of `CATEGORIE` (consider that a level 
is rare if it has less than 40 occurrences). Use tools from `forcats`. 

:::

::::: {.content-visible when-profile="solution"}  

::: {.callout-tip title="Solution"}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
df |> 
  count(CATEGORIE) |> 
  arrange(desc(n))
```

